'''Jacques Robbe''' (1643&ndash;1721) was a French engineer and geographer. He also wrote plays under the pseudonym '''Barquebois'''.<ref name="LamyWirtz2008">{{cite book|author1=Yves Lamy|author2=Jean Wirtz|title=Les anagrammes littéraires: pseudonymes et cryptonymes|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ByFoAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=13 January 2013|year=2008|publisher=Belin|isbn=978-2-7011-4714-7|page=52}}</ref>
==Life== Born in [[Soissons]], Robbe was educated as a lawyer.<ref>[http://www.jpmaps.co.uk/includes/biography.popup.cfm/id.1103 Jacques Robbe]. Accessed 13 January 2013.</ref> He became royal geographer, publishing a treatise on geography in 1678, which was translated into [[Turkish language|Turkish]] by Petros Baronian, the interpreter for the Dutch embassy in [[Istanbul]].<ref name="Vlahakis2006">{{cite book|author=George Vlahakis|title=Imperialism And Science: Social Impact And Interaction|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LYbbZHvtJi8C&pg=PA86|accessdate=13 January 2013|year=2006|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-85109-673-2|page=86}}</ref>
Robbe died in [[Paris]] in 1721.<ref name="Lancaster1940">{{cite book|author=Henry Carrington Lancaster|title=A History of French Dramatic Literature in the Seventeenth Century: The period of Racine, 1673-1700|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3FjrAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=13 January 2013|volume=2|year=1940|publisher=Johns Hopkins Press|page=519}}</ref>
==Works== * ''Methode pour apprendre facilement la geographie: dediée a monseigneur le duc du Mayne'', 2 vols., 1678 * (as M. de Barqubois) ''La rapinière, ou l'interessé: comédie'', 1683 * ''La femme testvë, ou, Le medecin Holandois: comedie'', 1686 * ''Les hazards du jeu de l'hombre'', 1700
